      "title": "Probe vs User-Flow Correlation — did the probe catch what users caught?",
      "type": "row"
    },
    {
      "datasource": {"type": "prometheus", "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"},
      "description": "Two series on a shared timeline: (A) chunk0_timeout rate observed by user flows (the actual symptom — handshake forwarded but no response bytes back), and (B) probe-error rate aggregated across all sub-probes. If the shapes track each other, the probe is exercising the same path as user traffic and `healthy = false` will follow on schedule. If A spikes while B stays flat, the probe is blind to the failure pattern: the dispatch path keeps tying new flows to a degraded uplink (per-flow rescue masks the issue), the global active never moves, and users see a split across uplinks. After the HTTPS-handshake probe is wired up, both lines should rise and fall together — that is the signal the probe is doing its job. Panels labelled by uplink + sub-probe so it is obvious which probe (http / https / ws) is the one tracking user reality.",
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {
          "color": {"mode": "palette-classic"},
          "custom": {"drawStyle": "line", "fillOpacity": 5, "lineWidth": 1, "showPoints": "auto"},
          "unit": "ops"
        }
      },
      "gridPos": {"h": 8, "w": 24, "x": 0, "y": 73},
      "id": 61,
      "options": {
        "legend": {"calcs": ["max", "lastNotNull"], "displayMode": "table", "placement": "bottom", "showLegend": true},
        "tooltip": {"mode": "multi", "sort": "desc"}
      },
      "targets": [
        {
          "expr": "sum by (uplink, transport) (rate(outline_ws_rust_uplink_runtime_failure_signatures_total{job=~\"$job\",instance=~\"$instance\",group=~\"$group\",signature=\"chunk0_timeout\"}[$__rate_interval]))",
          "legendFormat": "user-flow chunk0_timeout · {{transport}} {{uplink}}",
          "refId": "A"
        },
        {
          "expr": "sum by (uplink, transport, probe) (rate(outline_ws_rust_probe_runs_total{job=~\"$job\",instance=~\"$instance\",group=~\"$group\",result=\"err\"}[$__rate_interval]))",
          "legendFormat": "probe error · {{transport}} {{uplink}} {{probe}}",
          "refId": "B"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Probe Errors vs User-Flow chunk0_timeout (correlation)",
      "type": "timeseries"
    },
    {
      "datasource": {"type": "prometheus", "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"},
      "description": "Sticky-split detector. When the global active uplink degrades but probe still reports it healthy, individual TCP/UDP flows escape via per-flow rescue (cross-uplink failover) — and because strict-global + probe-enabled refuses to repoint the global active on a per-session success, every NEW flow then re-tries the still-pinned degraded uplink and either rescues again or pays the chunk0_timeout. Browser-tab sessions end up scattered across both uplinks: the user sees a split (some sites via uplink A, some via B) until either probe catches up, or all rescued flows drain naturally. The split window is exactly when {cross-uplink failover rate > 0} AND {uplink_health{from_uplink} == 1}: rescue is happening but the global pointer hasn't moved. After the HTTPS probe is wired up this gap should shrink — probe failure trips healthy=0 within probe.min_failures cycles, the active slides off, and new flows stop re-trying the degraded peer.",
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {
          "color": {"mode": "palette-classic"},
          "custom": {"drawStyle": "line", "fillOpacity": 10, "lineWidth": 1, "showPoints": "auto"},
          "unit": "ops"
        }
      },
      "gridPos": {"h": 8, "w": 12, "x": 0, "y": 81},
      "id": 62,
      "options": {
        "legend": {"calcs": ["max", "sum"], "displayMode": "table", "placement": "bottom", "showLegend": true},
        "tooltip": {"mode": "multi", "sort": "desc"}
      },
      "targets": [
        {
          "expr": "sum by (from_uplink, to_uplink, transport) (rate(outline_ws_rust_uplink_failovers_total{job=~\"$job\",instance=~\"$instance\",group=~\"$group\",transport=~\"tcp|udp\"}[$__rate_interval]))",
          "legendFormat": "cross-uplink rescue · {{transport}} {{from_uplink}}→{{to_uplink}}",
          "refId": "A"
        },
        {
          "expr": "outline_ws_rust_uplink_health{job=~\"$job\",instance=~\"$instance\",group=~\"$group\"}",
          "legendFormat": "health · {{transport}} {{uplink}}",
          "refId": "B"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Sticky-Split Detector — rescue × health",
      "type": "timeseries"
    },
    {
      "datasource": {"type": "prometheus", "uid": "${DS_PROMETHEUS}"},
      "description": "How often the probe-driven escalation actually fires. Each bar = one transition of `outline_ws_rust_uplink_health` (1↔0) over the rate-window — i.e. one moment when the probe verdict became authoritative enough to move the global active uplink. A flat-zero series during a chunk0_timeout episode visible elsewhere on this dashboard means the probe never crossed `min_failures` consecutive failures: either the probe-target is too easy (legacy plain http://example.com pattern) or `min_failures` / `runtime_failure_window` need a tighter setting. Healthy churn (1-2 flips/hour during a real outage, then 0) is the expected shape after the HTTPS probe is in place.",
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {
          "color": {"mode": "palette-classic"},
          "custom": {"drawStyle": "bars", "fillOpacity": 80, "lineWidth": 1, "showPoints": "never"},
          "unit": "none"
        }
      },
      "gridPos": {"h": 8, "w": 12, "x": 12, "y": 81},
      "id": 63,
      "options": {
        "legend": {"calcs": ["sum"], "displayMode": "table", "placement": "bottom", "showLegend": true},
        "tooltip": {"mode": "multi", "sort": "desc"}
      },
      "targets": [
        {
          "expr": "sum by (uplink, transport) (changes(outline_ws_rust_uplink_health{job=~\"$job\",instance=~\"$instance\",group=~\"$group\"}[$__rate_interval]))",
          "legendFormat": "{{transport}} {{uplink}}",
          "refId": "A"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Health Flips (per rate-window)",
      "type": "timeseries"
    }
